WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.480
Have you seen the wave of open source updates coming out of Posit lately?

00:00:03.520 --> 00:00:05.400
Here are the updates from the last month.

00:00:05.560 --> 00:00:06.360
GGSQL.

00:00:06.400 --> 00:00:08.760
This brings the grammar graphics directly to SQL.

00:00:08.800 --> 00:00:12.120
You can now define data visualizations inside your SQL queries

00:00:12.120 --> 00:00:13.720
without switching to R or Python.

00:00:13.760 --> 00:00:16.360
Quarto2, a complete rewrite of Quarto and Rust.

00:00:16.400 --> 00:00:19.680
It's faster and introduces native support for collaborative editing.

00:00:19.879 --> 00:00:24.400
Raghilda, a new Python package for building RAG with better transparency

00:00:24.400 --> 00:00:28.240
and default, observability in Shiny for Python and Point Blank, which now

00:00:28.240 --> 00:00:31.959
include built-in OpenTelemetry support for better production monitoring.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:36.400
TidyModels, updates across the core stack along with new AI agent skills

00:00:36.400 --> 00:00:37.680
and updated cheat sheets.

00:00:37.759 --> 00:00:40.279
Mori, a new R package for shared memory.

00:00:40.400 --> 00:00:44.119
It allows different processes to access the same data without copying it.

00:00:44.240 --> 00:00:49.400
TabPFN, an R interface for TabPFN, allowing you to use that foundation

00:00:49.400 --> 00:00:51.200
model for tabular data predictions.

00:00:51.439 --> 00:00:52.360
Nanoparquet.

00:00:52.599 --> 00:00:56.560
This package for Parquet files now supports list columns for nested data.

00:00:56.680 --> 00:00:57.240
Torch.

00:00:57.400 --> 00:01:00.799
The R ecosystem for Torch has expanded with more support for GPU

00:01:00.799 --> 00:01:02.240
management and computer vision.

00:01:02.480 --> 00:01:06.279
Roxygen2, new support for the S7 object system and improved

00:01:06.279 --> 00:01:07.919
documentation for R6.

00:01:07.959 --> 00:01:12.480
GreatDocs, a new library for Python designed specifically to make package

00:01:12.480 --> 00:01:15.639
documentation more readable and easier for LLMs to parse.

00:01:15.760 --> 00:01:18.519
We round up these updates in the Glimpse newsletter every month.

00:01:18.720 --> 00:01:20.199
Which one are you going to try first?

00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:21.519
Let us know in the comments.

